IT'S official! Dr Patrice Motsepe has been elected as the president of the Confederation of African Football (CAF). The South African mining billionaire is the first English-speaking to be elected as the Supremo of African Football in its 64 years of existence. Motsepe was the sole candidate for the presidential election at the 43rd CAF General Assembly currently underway in Rabat, Morocco. The 59-year-old billionaire becomes the eighth CAF president since its founding in 1957 and will replace predecessor, Malagasy politician Ahmad Ahmad. He is the first English-speaking Caf president in 64 years, ending the dominance of the francophone African countries. 